<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-093-127 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 175 013</DOCID><JOURNAL>Journal of Systems Management  August 1991 v42 n8 p20(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Models of communication. (communication used in informationsystems management) (System Notes) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Ware, Robb.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A theory suggests that computer programmers have excellentabstract thinking skills, while non-MIS individuals have onlyaverage abstract thinking skills.andP;  The difference in skill leveland usage may be one reason information systems (IS) professionalscan experience problems communicating with non-MIS workers andusers.andP;  IS professionals who want to improve their communicationsuccess rates can build scale models to communicate tonon-abstract thinkers about design plans.andP;  Models can includescreen displays, reports and the use of real data.andP;  Modeling is apositive technique because it can be done at the beginning of aproject to help users understand the project and to promote itssuccess.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     CommunicationInformation systemsProgrammersUser NeedsModelingProject Management.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>